05934nam a22007935i 9780674919990DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20182018mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806749199907 a10.4159/97806749199902doi  a(DE-B1597)501473  a(OCoLC)1030304393  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHF486.E6bM57 2018eb 7aHIS0150402bisacsh04a382.0941/052231 aMishra, Rupali, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Business of State :bCommerce, Politics, and the Birth of the East India Company /cRupali Mishra. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (370 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHarvard Historical Studies ;v18800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNote on Spelling, Dates, and Sources -- tIntroduction -- tPART ONE: GOVERNING THE COMPANY -- t1. The Patent and the Formation of the Company -- t2. Constituting Authority: The Court of Committees and the Generality -- t3. Wooing Adventurers: Membership and Useful Men -- t4. Division within the Company: The Problem of Faction and Representation -- t5. Merchants, Trading Companies, and Public Appeal -- tPART TWO: THE COMPANY AND THE STATE -- t6. The Changing Patent: Negotiating Privileges between Company and Regime -- t7. “What His Men Have Done Abroad”: Martial Engagements and the Company -- t8. The Dutch East India Company and Amboyna: Crisis and Response in the Company -- t9. Taking Stock and Looking Forward: The Difficulties of the Late 1620s -- t10. Crown Manipulations of the East Indies Trade: Dismantling the Company in the 1630s -- tConclusion -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tManuscript and Archival Sources -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt the height of its power around 1800, the English East India Company controlled half of the world’s trade and deployed a vast network of political influencers at home and abroad. Yet the story of the Company’s beginnings in the early seventeenth century has remained largely untold. Rupali Mishra’s account of the East India Company’s formative years sheds new light on one of the most powerful corporations in the history of the world. From its birth in 1600, the East India Company lay at the heart of English political and economic life. The Company’s fortunes were determined by the leading figures of the Stuart era, from the monarch and his privy counselors to an extended cast of eminent courtiers and powerful merchants. Drawing on a host of overlooked and underutilized sources, Mishra reconstructs the inner life of the Company, laying bare the era’s fierce struggles to define the difference between public and private interests and the use and abuse of power. Unlike traditional accounts, which portray the Company as a private entity that came to assume the powers of a state, Mishra’s history makes clear that, from its inception, the East India Company was embedded within—and inseparable from—the state. A Business of State illuminates how the East India Company quickly came to inhabit such a unique role in England’s commercial and political ambitions. It also offers critical insights into the rise of the early modern English state and the expansion and development of its nascent empire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aBusiness and politicszEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aCorporations, BritishzIndiaxHistoryy17th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / Stuart Era (1603-1714).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitl